  "prompt": "What should you do when you love someone but there's too much water under the bridge, even when they are making positive changes?",
  "response": "Here are some thoughtful perspectives:\n\n1. Self-reflection\n- Assess your true feelings and healing process\n- Consider if past hurt still overshadows potential growth\n- Be honest about whether you can genuinely forgive\n\n2. Communication\n- Have an open, honest dialogue about past issues\n- Listen to their perspective on changes they're making\n- Express your feelings and concerns clearly\n\n3. Emotional boundaries\n- Protect your emotional well-being\n- Recognize that positive changes don't automatically rebuild trust\n- Take time to process your emotions\n\n4. Potential paths forward\n- Consider potential reconciliation if changes seem genuine\n- Be open to rebuilding slowly and cautiously\n- Be prepared to walk away if healing isn't possible\n\n5. Personal healing\n- Focus on your own growth and emotional recovery\n- Seek therapy or counseling if needed\n- Don't feel obligated to reconnect just because they've changed\n\n6. Practical considerations\n- Evaluate the relationship's overall health\n- Consider whether past issues are truly resolvable\n- Think about long-term compatibility\n\n7. Emotional readiness\n- Be honest about whether you can truly move forward\n- Recognize that forgiveness is a personal journey\n- Don't rush yourself or feel pressured\n\nUltimately, prioritize your emotional health and make decisions that support your well-being.",
